1 (5) The training required under subsection (4):
2 (a) must focus solely on domestic and sexual violence and child abuse, including:
3 (i) child sexual abuse;
4 (ii) physical abuse;
5 (iii) emotional abuse;
6 (iv) coercive control;
7 (v) implicit and explicit bias, including biases relating to parents with disabilities;
8 (vi) trauma;
9 (vii) long-term and short-term impacts of domestic violence and child abuse on children; and
10 (viii) victim and perpetrator behavior patterns and relationship dynamics within the cycle of violence;
11 (b) must be provided by:
12 (i) a professional with substantive experience in assisting survivors of domestic violence or child
13 abuse, including a victim service provider as defined in 34 U.S.C. 12291; and
14 (ii) if possible, a survivor of domestic violence or child physical or sexual abuse;
15 (c) must rely on evidence-based and peer-reviewed research by recognized experts in the types of
16 abuse described in subsection (5)(a);
17 (d) may not include theories, concepts, or belief systems unsupported by the research described in
18 subsection (5)(c); and
19 (e) must be designed to improve the ability of courts to:
20 (i) recognize and respond to child physical abuse, child sexual abuse, domestic violence, and
21 trauma in all family victims, particularly children; and
22 (ii) make appropriate custody recommendations that prioritize child safety and well-being and are
23 culturally sensitive and appropriate for diverse communities.
